Wrangling data

Introduction

Letâs load in our usual librariesâ¦

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)

This tutorial is going to be a bit hard, so you might need to work through it in sections!

The last time we thought about datatypes, it was in our very first tutorial. We learned that functions like readr::read_csv are more explicit about datatypes than their âbase-Râ equivalents like utils::read.csv. In that tutorial, we also briefly alluded to the fact that R is (by default) a weakly-typed language, and that the tidyverse provides a (relatively) strongly-typed alternative to many base-R functions.

Below, weâll reproduce the example introduced in the first tutorial:

Code 
# Here's the year 2020, saved as a string
this_year <- "2020"

# We're making sure that the variable is a string, not a number
is.character(this_year)
[1] TRUE
Code 
is.numeric(this_year)
[1] FALSE
Code 
# Now we test whether this string is equal to the number 2,020
this_year == 2020
[1] TRUE

This simple example illustrates how weakly-typed languages have the potential to create headaches through implicit conversion. Part of the appeal of the tidyverse is that its functions are designed to stop implicit conversion from happening. This can be annoying if you feel that strong typing is pedantic, but it usually ends up saving you a lot of time and grief in the long run.

Now that weâve grown more comfortable with basic data wrangling operations, itâs time to deepen our understanding of datatypes.

Type-checking

Type errors occur most frequently when youâre performing mutating operations. To illustrate, letâs open up a dataset classifying U.S. states into regions, and save that data to a variable called regions. This is the state_region_division.csv file from the data folder.

regions <- here("data", "state_region_division.csv") %>%

To our surprise, this results in an error. What happened? Strictly speaking, NA is encoded as a logical datatype in R. Since weâre working with tidyverse functions, we canât mix-and-match logical datatypes (NA) with character datatypes (regions$region). Instead, we have to use datatype-specific variants of NA to make this work.

Code 
regions %>%
  filter(region == "Midwest") %>%
  mutate(
    region = if_else(division == "West North Central", NA_character_, division)
  )

You should also know that thereâs a great generalization of dplyr::if_else for when you want to make multiple substitutions, using dplyr::case_when. Note that the order in which you check for conditions matters. We can illustrate this using this very opinionated alteration of region labels:

Code 
regions %>%
  mutate(
    new_regions = case_when(
      region == "Northeast" ~ "Too dang cold",
      state == "New York" ~ "Dang Yankees",
      division == "West North Central" ~ NA_character_,
      state == "Oregon" | state == "Washington" ~ "Pacific Northwest",
      TRUE ~ region
    )
  ) %>%
  print(n = 51)

Lots of things to note here!

  1. Conditions are on the left-hand-side (LHS), replacements are on the right-hand-side (RHS), and theyâre separated by the tilde (~) operator.
  2. You can see that you can mix-and-match conditions as you please. Some of these mutating changes were based off region, others off state, others still on division, and some were based on a logical condition containing the OR (| vertical bar) operator.
  3. What happened to our labeling of New York as the âDang Yankeesâ regions? Why didnât that work? What would it take to fix it? Try it yourself.
  4. What does the very last condition do, and what happens if you remove it?

Factors

The factor datatype in R is for discrete variables. These factors can be purely categorical (e.g., apple, banana, pear), or can be ordinal (i.e., ordered categories, e.g., being the first, second, or third child). In either case, factors have levels that correspond to each distinct/discrete value contained in that variable.

To help wrangle factor datatypes, tidyverse automatically loads the package forcats when calling library(tidyverse). Functions belonging to forcats are easily identifiable, as theyâre all prefixed by fct_.

Conceptually, factors are not hard to understand, but they have historically caused a great deal of drama and headache for R users. This isnât strictly necessary for you to know, but if youâre curious, itâs time for one of my famous digressions. From 1998-2020, the utils::read.csv default behavior was to import all strings (i.e., text-based data) as factors. Why is this a problem? Imagine that you sent out a survey with a free-response question. Every user types in a unique response. Now, you open up the dataset in R, andâ¦ instead of treating these responses like text data, your dataframe contains a factor column with thousands of levels. In contrast, readr::read_csv has never read strings as factors, and this is a major reason why many people preferred using the tidyverse solution over the base function.

Starting with R 4.0, the utils::read.csv default has changed so that strings are not read as factors. This is great, as for the most part, you can treat strings like theyâre strings. But sometimes, youâll want to convert text-based data into factors. There are two main use cases for doing this:

  1. Youâre doing some sort of statistical analysis with categorical/ordinal variables, and you need to change what the âreference categoryâ is.
  2. Youâre plotting data, and youâd like to (manually) reorder some categories for visual clarity.

Weâll ignore the first point for now, as this tutorial series is about data wrangling, not statistics. But, if you move onto the learning-stats-backwards tutorial series after completing this series, youâll learn all about reference categories! But the second point is a very useful one, and crops up all the time in the course of data wrangling.

To illustrate, letâs open up a dataset containing popular baby names in New York City. In the data folder is a CSV file named Popular_Baby_Names.csv. Read it into a dataframe. The variable names are not tidy-friendly, so letâs do something about that.

There is not a standard capitalization scheme in this dataset, so weâll impose one. You havenât yet learned about this (coming up next!), so you can just use the following to do this:

Code 
baby <- stuff_here %>%
  mutate(name = str_to_title(childs_first_name)) %>%
  more_stuff_here

For the time being, letâs restrict our analysis so that weâre only looking at names of Hispanic female babies. Weâll only be looking at the variables year_of_birth, name, and count. The variable name year_of_birth is a little clunky, so letâs shorten that to year.

Do you notice anything else thatâs âmessyâ about this dataset? If not, try arranging the dataset by year and count. Do you notice it now? Letâs do something about that.

Code 
baby <- here("data", "Popular_Baby_Names.csv") %>%
  read_csv() %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  # Standardize name capitalization
  mutate(name = str_to_title(childs_first_name)) %>%
  # For simplicity, restrict to a single demographic
  filter(ethnicity == "HISPANIC" & gender == "FEMALE") %>%
  select(
    year = year_of_birth,
    name, count
  ) %>%
  # Make pretty
  arrange(year, count) %>%
  # Get rid of duplicate observations
  distinct()

Okay, now that weâve got ourselves a fairly tidy dataset, letâs do something fun. One of the big revolutions in text analysis is finding a way to quantify the âsimilarityâ or âdistanceâ between pieces of text. Some of these are more abstract, like assigning words to a particular set of coordinates within high-dimensional embedding spaces. Others are more concrete, like the Levenshtein distance, which is defined as âthe minimal number of single-character edits (insertions, deletions or substitutions) required to change one word into the otherâ (from Wikipedia).

Weâll be using the Levenshtein distance to quantify how (dis)similar names are to each other, and then weâll see how factors can help us plot that data cleanly.

Weâll want a variable named unique_names, which is a vector containing the 50 most popular names of all time, arranged in alphabetical order. You may find it useful to read the documentation for tibble::deframe to accomplish part of this.

Code 
unique_names <- baby %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  mutate(all_time_popularity = sum(count)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = year, values_from = count) %>%
  slice_max(all_time_popularity, n = 50) %>%
  select(name) %>%
  arrange(name) %>%
  deframe()

Once we have that vector, itâs very easy to compute the distance matrix. We havenât worked with matrices before, so letâs try to get this back into a dataframe as quickly as possible. Youâll note that weâre using a function from stringr, which we havenât yet covered, but the function name makes it clear what it does.

Code 
name_distances <- adist(unique_names) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  # Label rows
  mutate(from = unique_names) %>%
  # Convert into "tidy" format
  pivot_longer(
    cols = -from,
    names_to = "identifier",
    values_to = "lev_dist"
  ) %>%
  # Need to replace automatic header names with labels
  mutate(
    identifier = str_remove(identifier, "V"),
    identifier = as.numeric(identifier)
  ) %>%
  left_join(enframe(unique_names, name = "identifier", value = "to")) %>%
  # Make pretty
  select(from, to, lev_dist)

Now, letâs try plotting these results in a heatmap.

Code 
name_distances %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=to, y=from, fill=lev_dist)) +
  geom_tile()

Phew. There are obviously many things we could do to improve this plot. For example, we could try rotating the x-axis label text, using a better colormap for the fill aesthetic, and forcing the plot to be square.

Code 
name_distances %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=to, y=from, fill=lev_dist)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma") +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 1, hjust = 1)
  )

But thereâs something a little more subtle that we might want to change also. When we read a heatmap, weâre often accustomed to the y-axis labels being ordered from the top-downwards. Here, the plot is organized in alphabetical order from the bottom-upwards.

This is where factors come in handy! Iâve hidden the code block below so that I donât give away the answers to the previous part of the exercise, but you can go ahead and open it up. The key is using forcats::fct_rev to reverse the factor order.

Code 
name_distances %>%
  mutate(from = fct_rev(from)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=to, y=from, fill=lev_dist)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma") +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 1, hjust = 1)
  )

Now we can clearly see that (e.g.) Ariana and Arianna are quantified as being very similar to each other, as are Emely, Emily, and Emma. We can also see that Elizabeth is one of the most dissimilar names from any other name in this set.

There are many other useful functions in forcats, many of which take inspiration from analogous functions for handling non-factor data. Weâll cover one more in todayâs tutorial, which I personally find very useful in my day-to-day workflows.

Letâs say that weâre particularly interested in highlighting the fact that Elizabeth is very dissimilar from other names, such that we want to place that name as the first entry in the heatmap. This is very easy to do using forcats::fct_relevel, which allows you to manually specify factor ordering.

Code 
name_distances %>%
  mutate(
    from = fct_relevel(from, "Elizabeth"),
    to = fct_relevel(to, "Elizabeth"),
    from = fct_rev(from)
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=to, y=from, fill=lev_dist)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma") +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 1, hjust = 1)
  )

Note that other levels of the fact have been left alone. You can do this with as many levels as youâd like. Letâs do it with Kimberly too.

Code 
name_distances %>%
  mutate(
    from = fct_relevel(from, "Elizabeth", "Kimberly"),
    to = fct_relevel(to, "Elizabeth", "Kimberly"),
    from = fct_rev(from)
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=to, y=from, fill=lev_dist)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma") +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 1, hjust = 1)
  )

Strings

The string datatype is pretty easy to understand: itâs basically anything that is stored as text. This includes numbers that arenât really numbers, like ZIP codes. (Remember our first tutorial, where we encountered difficulties with ZIP codes like 02912 getting converted into the number 2,912?)

Historically, R has had great tools for working with numbers, and pretty mediocre tools for working with strings (not least reading strings as factors!). This is what motivated the development of the stringr package, which is part of the default set of tidyverse packages loaded when calling library(tidyverse).

Itâs fairly easy to find stringr functions, as theyâre all prefixed by str_ before the description of what they do. In my day-to-day workflows, I typically think about stringr functions as they pertain to two major operations: mutate and filter, and weâll go over examples of each.

Concatenation

This is about the easiest example we can use to introduce stringr. We know that we can concatenate things into vectors using c(...). For example:

Code 
c("apple", "banana", "pear")
[1] "apple"  "banana" "pear"

Using similar syntax, we can concatenate strings. If all inputs are âflatâ (i.e., not vectors), then the output will also be a flat string. If a single input is a vector, but all other inputs are flat, then the output will combine the flat string with all elements of the vector. Finally, if all inputs are vectors, then all inputs must have the same number of elements, and the output will combine the vectors element-wise.

Code 
# All inputs are flat
str_c("I need", "apples, bananas, and pears", sep = " ")
[1] "I need apples, bananas, and pears"
Code 
# One input is a vector
str_c("I need", c("apples", "bananas", "pears"), sep = " ")
[1] "I need apples"  "I need bananas" "I need pears"
Code 
# Multiple inputs are vectors
str_c(
  c("I need", "I want", "I like"),
  c("apples", "bananas", "pears"),
  sep = " "
)
[1] "I need apples"  "I want bananas" "I like pears"

Capitalization

Okay, letâs say that weâre working for the city government, and thereâs an urban planner whoâs interested in seeing whether certain ZIP codes contain more commercial versus residential condos. Already, we might suspect this will require the use of a filtering operation. If youâve completed the mini-exercise from the previous paragraph, you know that this is one way you could solve this problem:

Code 
tax %>%
  filter(
    short_desc == "Commercial Condo" |
    short_desc == "Residential Condo"
  )

That solution is easy enough when weâre working with a relatively simple toy problem from a relatively simple toy dataset. But, things can quicklyget more complicated.

What if, in the future, the city decides to classify some properties as being âindustrialâ condos? (Ignore the fact that thereâs no such thing as an industrial condo, itâs a toy problem.) Then, youâd be missing out on an entire class of condos because youâre only looking for two classes of condos.

Or perhaps, in the future, the city might release datasets where the descriptions are written as "commercial" and "residential" condos. Obviously, to a human, we know those are the same as "Commercial" and "Residential" condos, but computers donât know that. To prove this, try running the following:

In both of these relatively plausible cases, our code would fail to work with updated versions of the cityâs property tax datasets. Weâd like to future-proof our code as much as we can. But how?

When working with text data, one of the most common mutating operations is to standardize capitalization to avoid matching errors. This is trivially easy to do with stringr.

Regular expressions

Those string filtering examples were pretty easy, so letâs try something harder. The city government of Providence now wants us to say something about the distribution of Commercial I properties in various ZIP codes. We know a priori that Commercial II properties are part of the 2020 dataset, and weâre not sure whether Commercial III or Commercial IV properties might show up in future datasets. Naively, we can try doing the exact same thing we did before:

Code 
tax %>%
  mutate(short_desc = str_to_lower(short_desc)) %>%
  filter(str_detect(short_desc, "commercial i")) %>%
  print(n = 5)
# A tibble: 1,457 Ã 2
  short_desc    zip_postal
  <chr>         <chr>     
1 commercial ii 02907     
2 commercial ii <NA>      
3 commercial i  02904     
4 commercial ii 02906     
5 commercial i  02909     
# â¦ with 1,452 more rows

To our surprise, we get both I and II returned in the results. Why? Itâs because stringr functions donât perform literal pattern matching, but instead use regular expressions (âregexâ). Regex is not an R-specific construction, and is used in (virtually?) all modern programming languages, though the exact implementation can differ from language to language.

I cannot teach you regex in this tutorial. There are too many nuances and complexities, and itâs beyond the scope of what weâre trying to do here. As usual, my goal is not to guide you to complete data wrangling mastery, but to build up enough scaffolding that youâre capable enough to learn more advanced topics on your own.

However, I can provide a few toy examples to help you gain a quick intuition, and once you have an intuition, you can get exact details from the comprehensive guide on the stringr documentation website, which I reference at least twice a week.

Regex anchoring

The big idea behind regex is that you can use abstract patterns to match specific text features. For example, you can use string anchoring to match the start of a string using ^ and the end of a string using $. This is sufficient to devise one solution to our problem:

Code 
tax %>%
  mutate(short_desc = str_to_lower(short_desc)) %>%
  filter(str_detect(short_desc, "^commercial i$")) %>%
  print(n = 5)
# A tibble: 523 Ã 2
  short_desc   zip_postal
  <chr>        <chr>     
1 commercial i 02904     
2 commercial i 02909     
3 commercial i 02904     
4 commercial i 02901     
5 commercial i 02904     
# â¦ with 518 more rows

Why does this anchoring solution work? Weâll use str_extract_all to help us gain an intuition.

Code 
# This replicates the pattern we'd first tried
# The pattern matches both strings!
str_extract_all(
  string = c("commercial i", "commercial ii"),
  pattern = "commercial i"
)
[[1]]
[1] "commercial i"

[[2]]
[1] "commercial i"
Code 
# Now we can see why anchoring solves this problem!
str_extract_all(
  string = c("commercial i", "commercial ii"),
  pattern = "^commercial i$"
)
[[1]]
[1] "commercial i"

[[2]]
character(0)

Regex repetition

Another useful abstract pattern is matching repetitions of a desired text feature. Letâs pretend that in the future, the city of Providence does add Commercial III and Commercial IV to their datasets. If we were interested in matching I-III, but not IV, how would we do this? We can use some of the following patterns:

  • *: 0 or more matches
  • ?: 0 or 1 matches
  • +: 1 or more matches
  • {n}: exactly n matches
  • {n,}: at least n matches
  • {n,m}: at least n matches, and at most m matches
Code 
str_extract(
  string = c(
    "commercial i", "commercial ii", "commercial iii", "commercial iv"
  ),
  pattern = "^commercial i*$"
)
[1] "commercial i"   "commercial ii"  "commercial iii" NA
Code 
str_extract(
  string = c(
    "commercial i", "commercial ii", "commercial iii", "commercial iv"
  ),
  pattern = "^commercial i?$"
)
[1] "commercial i" NA             NA             NA
Code 
str_extract(
  string = c(
    "commercial i", "commercial ii", "commercial iii", "commercial iv"
  ),
  pattern = "^commercial i+$"
)
[1] "commercial i"   "commercial ii"  "commercial iii" NA
Code 
# Note that we've stopped using the anchors, for demonstration purposes
str_extract(
  string = c(
    "commercial i", "commercial ii", "commercial iii", "commercial iv"
  ),
  pattern = "commercial i{2}"
)
[1] NA              "commercial ii" "commercial ii" NA
Code 
str_extract(
  string = c(
    "commercial i", "commercial ii", "commercial iii", "commercial iv"
  ),
  pattern = "commercial i{2,}"
)
[1] NA               "commercial ii"  "commercial iii" NA
Code 
str_extract(
  string = c(
    "commercial i", "commercial ii", "commercial iii", "commercial iv"
  ),
  pattern = "commercial i{2,3}"
)
[1] NA               "commercial ii"  "commercial iii" NA

  • Along the same lines, letâs say that we were interested in matching the i in commercial i exactly once. Naively, we might think to specify commercial i{1}. Why would that fail? What are better solutions to this problem?
